First,&nbsp;notice&nbsp;that&nbsp;the&nbsp;doublet,&nbsp;I,&nbsp;contains/our&nbsp;singlets&nbsp;This<br>
is&nbsp;typical&nbsp;of&nbsp;quantum&nbsp;logic&nbsp;but&nbsp;an&nbsp;incomprehensible&nbsp;contra-<br>diction&nbsp;to&nbsp;classical&nbsp;logic&nbsp;wherein&nbsp;eveiy&nbsp;doublet,&nbsp;by&nbsp;definition,<br>contains&nbsp;only<i>&nbsp;two</i>&nbsp;singlets,&nbsp;no&nbsp;more&nbsp;and&nbsp;no&nbsp;less&nbsp;Lattices&nbsp;are<br>graphic&nbsp;demonstrations&nbsp;of&nbsp;the&nbsp;quantum&nbsp;postulate&nbsp;that&nbsp;there&nbsp;is<br>always&nbsp;at&nbsp;least&nbsp;one&nbsp;alternative&nbsp;between&nbsp;every&nbsp;&quot;this&quot;&nbsp;and&nbsp;every<br>
